node.text:
For those of you that don’t know, Emma is my service dog for PTSD. It’s been pretty challenging for me to get her trained to the level that I want her to be at this age (6 months old). I truly commend people who train their own dog for their disability. It really is a challenge. I got SO lucky with Phoebe. She was my service dog as well but didn’t become it until later in life. I swear she knew what I was thinking and she helped me tremendously. Emma I am extremely proud of for retaining new information extremely well. Where she suffers is her “sharpness” to each command. She will do them, but you see she does them in a more casual state. I will let all the commands in this video sly though because since her spay, I’ve been giving her CBD oil to help keep her calm so she can heal. It has had an effect on her mental sharpness. I also haven’t done any training with her for over a week, so I’m proud of her for her efforts today. 
Her “tasks” that help with me with my PTSD are; walking behind me to separate others from me because people walking too close behind me is a trigger for me. When she’s there, I can relax because all I feel is puppy behind my legs ☺️ she also will sit behind me when queuing so I have her as a barrier between me and the other person, or sometimes I have her sit between my legs. 
I will kneel down and have her give me a “hug” when I get anxious. Definitely helpful when I feel my heart rate start to increase. I’m still working on her doing those commands automatically and not without me having to tell her with treats. I’m also working on having her apply pressure on my chest when a panic attack begins to arise and also to lick my face. She actually has done that on her own already, so I’m not sure how to “train” it into her, or for now trust that she just “knows.” There are still some more tasks I need to teach her. But this is where we are right now. I’m starting with the ones that are most helpful to me and then will add more as I feel like she’s perfecting where she’s at. 
I’m trying my best with her training and like I said before, I am very proud of her and she really has become an asset to my mental health.
